Rocket 79: The NVS, previously IRNSS, constellation is not a global positioning constellation, like GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, or Beidou-3, but a regional one, similar to the Chinese Beidou-1 and 2, or the Japanese QZSS, serving only the Indian sub-continent. IRNSS satellites have two payloads: a navigation payload and CDMA ranging payload in addition to a laser retro-reflector. The payload generates navigation signals at L5 and S-band. The design of the payload makes the IRNSS system interoperable and compatible with Global Positioning System (GPS) and Galileo systems. The satellite is powered by two solar arrays, which generate up to 1,660 watts, and has a lifetime of ten years.

Rocket 447: VICTUS NOX is a payload for the US Space Force's Space Systems Command. It will perform a Space Domain Awareness (SDA) mission in LEO. VICTUS NOX is a mission meant to demonstrate the United States' ability to rapidly place a satellite in orbit if the need arises. To that end, the payload was delivered to Firefly, encapsulated, and readied for launch. The US Space Force would then give the go-ahead for Firefly to launch sometime in 2023, at which point Firefly had just 24 hours to send the payload to orbit. When the US Space Force gave their go-ahead, Firefly successfully launched the satellite within their Firefly Alpha launcher within the specified 24-hour period.

SLIM aims to soft-land with an accuracy range of 100 m. In comparison, the accuracy of the Apollo 11 Eagle lunar module was an elliptic which was 20 km wide in downrange and 5 km wide in crossrange. According to Yoshifumi Inatani, deputy director general of the JAXA Institute of Space and Astronautical Science (ISAS), succeeding in this extremely precise landing, will lead to enhancing the quality of space exploration.

Rocket 519: The NVS, previously IRNSS, constellation is not a global positioning constellation, like GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, or Beidou-3, but a regional one, similar to the Chinese Beidou-1 and 2, or the Japanese QZSS, serving only the Indian sub-continent. IRNSS satellites have two payloads: a navigation payload and CDMA ranging payload in addition to a laser retro-reflector. The payload generates navigation signals at L5 and S-band. The design of the payload makes the IRNSS system interoperable and compatible with Global Positioning System (GPS) and Galileo systems. The satellite is powered by two solar arrays, which generate up to 1,660 watts, and has a lifetime of ten years.

Rocket 522: The Time-Resolved Observations of Precipitation structure and storm Intensity with a Constellation of Smallsats (TROPICS) mission will provide rapid-refresh microwave measurements over the tropics that can be used to observe the thermodynamics of the troposphere and precipitation structure for storm systems at the mesoscale and synoptic scale over the entire storm lifecycle. TROPICS comprises a constellation of CubeSats in three low-Earth orbital planes. Each CubeSat will host a high-performance radiometer scanning across the satellite track at 30 RPM to provide temperature profiles using seven channels near the 118.75 GHz oxygen absorption line, water vapor profiles using 3 channels near the 183 GHz water vapor absorption line, imagery in a single channel near 90 GHz for precipitation measurements, and a single channel at 206 GHz for cloud ice measurements.
Rocket 523: The Unity 25 mission was a flight test for VSS Unity and Virgin Galactic's fifth crewed spaceflight. It was also the first mission with a new version of the SpaceShipTwo spacecraft and carried a full crew of two pilots and four mission specialists in the cockpit.
Rocket 524: NEXTSat 2 is a microsatellite designed and developed at SaTReC (Satellite Technology Research Center) of KAIST (Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology) for a X-band radar technology demonstration.
Rocket 525: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-23 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 176th flight of a Progress.
Rocket 526: First space flight by a Saudi female astronaut. First landing of a booster from a crewed mission on land at LZ-1.
Rocket 527: Macau Science Satellite-1 (MUST-1A/B) are 2 magnetosphere research satellites from the Macau University of Science and Technology (MUST) aiming to study the different layers of the Earth’s magnetosphere system, particularly in the South Atlantic Anomaly by studying the origin and evolution of the geomagnetic field and the geomagnetic inversion mechanism, and draw a high-precision and high-resolution lithospheric geomagnetic map.
Rocket 528: One of the 16 OneWeb satellites is a demonstration version of the second generation of these satellites which will be deployed in the future to increase the capabilities of the constellation.
Rocket 529: SpaceX launch of a batch of Starlink v2-mini satellites for their second generation high-speed low earth orbit internet satellite constellation.
Rocket 530: BeiDou-3 will eventually consist of 35 satellites and is expected to provide global services upon completion in 2020. When fully completed, BeiDou will provide an alternative global navigation satellite system to the United States-owned Global Positioning System (GPS) and is expected to be more accurate than the GPS. It was claimed in 2016 that BeiDou-3 will reach millimeter-level accuracy (with post-processing), which is ten times more accurate than the finest level of GPS.
Rocket 531: Launch consists of Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 532: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for its first generation high-speed low-Earth orbit internet satellite constellation.
Rocket 533: The Tianzhou (Chinese: 天舟; lit. 'Heavenly Ship') is a Chinese automated cargo spacecraft developed from China's first prototype space station Tiangong-1 to resupply its future modular space station. It was first launched (Tianzhou 1) on the Long March 7 rocket on April 20, 2017, and demonstrated autonomous propellant transfer (space refueling).
Rocket 534: The Time-Resolved Observations of Precipitation structure and storm Intensity with a Constellation of Smallsats (TROPICS) mission will provide rapid-refresh microwave measurements over the tropics that can be used to observe the thermodynamics of the troposphere and precipitation structure for storm systems at the mesoscale and synoptic scale over the entire storm lifecycle. TROPICS comprises a constellation of CubeSats in three low-Earth orbital planes. Each CubeSat will host a high-performance radiometer scanning across the satellite track at 30 RPM to provide temperature profiles using seven channels near the 118.75 GHz oxygen absorption line, water vapor profiles using 3 channels near the 183 GHz water vapor absorption line, imagery in a single channel near 90 GHz for precipitation measurements, and a single channel at 206 GHz for cloud ice measurements.
Rocket 535: Launch consists of Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 536: First Falcon Heavy launch to expend all three cores, and first Falcon Heavy launch to use flight-proven fairing halves. Additionally, this was the 100th reuse of flight-proven fairing halves in the Falcon family, and the furthest downrange recovery of fairing halves, at 1960km downrange.
Rocket 537: The O3b mPower satellites are improved second generation satellites for the SES owned O3b Networks.
Rocket 538: SpaceX launch of a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 539: The Unity 24 mission was a flight test for the VSS Unity and SpaceShipTwo following several upgrades. The spacecraft was released from the VSS Unity and performed a flyby to verify some technologies, no use was made of the engine.
Rocket 540: TeLEOS-2 is a Singaporean Earth Observation satellite built by ST Electronics (Satellite Systems). It carries a made-in-Singapore Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) capable of providing 1 m resolution data. It will be equipped with a 500 GB onboard recorder for recording the data captured and a high-speed 800 Mbps downlink.
Rocket 541: First integrated launch of Starship and Super Heavy. With this launch, Starship became the most powerful rocket ever to launch.
Rocket 542: SpaceX launch of a batch of Starlink v2-Mini satellites for their second generation high-speed low Earth orbit internet satellite constellation.
Rocket 543: Fengyun-3G is a dedicated Low Earth Orbit precipitation measurement satellite, previously named FY-3RM-1, of the FY-3 series of Chinese Low Earth Orbit weather satellites.
Rocket 544: This launch will debut a new MVac nozzle extension design aimed at increasing cadence and reducing costs. This new nozzle extension is shorter and, as a result, the engine has a lower specific impulse and therefore performance. Due to this, it will only fly on missions that don't need Falcon 9's full performance capability.
Rocket 546: Intelsat 40e is an advanced geostationary satellite that will provide Intelsat’s government and enterprise customers across North and Central America with high-throughput, “coast-to-coast” services. The satellite’s capabilities will support the growing number of customers that depend on Intelsat’s managed services and solutions to easily integrate satellite into their overall networking and communications strategies.
Rocket 547: Test launch of Hyperbola-1 to test reliability after 3 successive failures in 2021-22.
Rocket 548: Transport Tranche 0 is an interoperable mesh network of tens of satellites for the United States Space Force (USSF) Space Development Agency (SDA) to provide periodic low-latency and high-capacity data connectivity between on orbit satellites and forces on the ground.
Rocket 549: First launch of the Tianlong-2 and first launch for the Chinese private company Space Pioneer. This launch makes Tianlong-2 the first RP-1-based private rocket from China to reach orbit.
Rocket 550: Yaogan 34 is an optical remote sensing satellite, with a ground image resolution of a few meters, mainly used for land census, urban planning, land rights, road network design, crop yield estimation, and disaster prevention and mitigation. It was built by SAST.
Rocket 551: 4 X-band synthetic-aperture radar Earth observation satellites for PIESAT (1 main, 3 sub-satellites), operating in tandem using very long baseline interferometry, with resolution at 0.5 - 5 m.
Rocket 552: Launch consists of Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 554: Ofek-13 is an Israeli SAR (Synthetic Aperture Radar) reconnaissance satellite. It combines high resolution with large area coverage using electronic beam steering.
Rocket 555: The 18th flight dedicated to the OneWeb high-speed Internet constellation. The initial constellation consists of 648 satellites. Later, the constellation could be expanded to more than 900 satellites depending on demand. OneWeb is expected to begin customer demonstrations in 2022, then provide a global, 24-hour service in 2022/2023.
Rocket 556: Launch consists of Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 557: BlackSky 9 and 10 are part of sixty high-resolution Earth observation microsatellites in the BlackSky constellation. This constellation will provide real-time earth observation. the constellation is built by Blacksky, a SpaceFlight Subsidiary, and the satellites are produced by LeoStella LLC, a joint venture of Spaceflight Industries and Thales Alenia Space.
Rocket 559: 2nd stage engine failed to reach full thrust after slow response of main valves and failure in pressure increase of the liquid oxygen turbopump. Presence of vapor bubble at the LOX pump inlet is suspected.
Rocket 560: Return to flight for the Kuaizhou 1A after its previous flight failed.
Rocket 561: Launched 4 hours and 12 minutes after Starlink Group 2-8 from California, marking SpaceX's shortest period between two launches as of liftoff, and passing the previous record by 3 hours.
Rocket 562: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their first generation high-speed low earth orbit internet satellite constellation.
Rocket 563: Gaofen 13 (GF 13) is a series of geostationary Earth observation satellites in the Gaofen series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites.
Rocket 564: The mission dubbed "Stronger Together" carries Capella Space's Capella 9 and 10 satellites. The improved satellites are about twice as large as the Capella 1 (Denali) prototype to accommodate a bigger sensor aperture for the X-band Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) that can provide high-contrast, low-noise high-resolution sub-0.5 meter imagery. For this, it features a new 3.5-meter aperture deployed mesh-based reflector antenna.
Rocket 565: Chinese Earth observation satellite of unknown purposes.
Rocket 566: SpaceX CRS-27 is a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. The mission is contracted by NASA and will be flown by SpaceX using a Cargo Dragon.
Rocket 567: Horus 2 is a remote sensing satellite for the Egyptian Space Agency developed by Aerospace Dongfanghong Satellite Co., Ltd. of CAST.
Rocket 568: Olimp-K, also designated Luch, is a Russian geostationary satellite built for the Russian Ministry of Defence and the Russian intelligence agency FSB. The objectives of the missions have not been published.
Rocket 569: Described as satellites for cartography purposes, details TBD.
Rocket 570: The 17th flight dedicated to the OneWeb high-speed Internet constellation. The initial constellation consists of 648 satellites. Later, the constellation could be expanded to more than 900 satellites depending on demand. OneWeb is expected to begin customer demonstrations in 2022, then provide a global, 24-hour service in 2022/2023.
Rocket 571: 2nd stage engine failed to ignite due to electrical circuit failure between vehicle controller and engine igniter at engine ignition.
Rocket 572: Failure officially reported by Israel and not confirmed by Iranian sources. Possible re-launch of satellite lost in pre-launch failure of the Safir rocket on 29 August 2019.
Rocket 573: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their first generation high-speed low earth orbit internet satellite constellation.
Rocket 574: SpaceX Crew-6 is the sixth operational crewed rotation mission of a Crew Dragon spacecraft to the International Space Station. The crew will consist of commander Stephen Bowen (NASA), pilot Warren Hoburg (NASA), and mission specialists Andrey Fediaev (Roscosmos) and Sultan Al Neyadi (MBRSC)
Rocket 575: First launch of Starlink v2 satellites. These are downsized versions of the V2 satellites intended to launch on Starship but built to fit within Falcon 9's payload fairing and are colloquially known as "Starlink V2 Mini."
Rocket 576: Horus 1 is a remote sensing satellite for the Egyptian Space Agency developed by Aerospace Dongfanghong Satellite Co., Ltd. of CAST.
Rocket 577: Soyuz MS-23 was launched without crew, and will automatically dock to the ISS to replace the Soyuz MS-22 spacecraft that suffered a thermal control system depressurization/leak on the ISS on December 15, 2022.
Rocket 578: ChinaSat 26 (Zhongxing 26) is a Chinese high throughput (HTS) Ka-band communications satellite based on the DFH-4E satellite bus for serving the Greater East Asia-Australia area.
Rocket 579: Inmarsat I-6 F2 is a geostationary communications satellite built by Airbus. F2 will carry a large 9m aperture L-band antenna and nine multibeam Ka-band antennas, and feature a high level of flexibility and connectivity. A new generation modular digital processor will provide full routing flexibility over up to 8000 channels and dynamic power allocation to over 200 spot beams in L-band. Ka-band spot beams will be steerable over the full Earth disk, with flexible channel to beam allocation.
Rocket 580: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 581: Launch consisted of 55 Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second-generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 582: EOS-07 is a small Indian earth observing satellite developed by ISRO. The satellite is being realised based on Microsat-TD to demonstrate launch on demand capability with SSLV. It is expected to meet the increasing user demands for cartographic applications at cadastral level, urban and rural management, coastal land use and regulation, utilities mapping, development and various other GIS applications.
Rocket 583: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-22 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 175th flight of a Progress.
Rocket 584: The Amazonas Nexus is a High Throughput Satellite (HTS) designed with an innovative architecture that combines the Ku and Ka bands to optimize communications and multiply the capacity available for commercial use. The satellite will also feature the latest generation Digital Transparent Processor (DTP), a technological advance that will be able to digitally process the satellite's received signals and increase its flexibility in orbit.
Rocket 585: Elektro-L n°4 is a Russian geostationary weather satellite. It is the fourth Elektro-L spacecraft to fly. It replaces the first Elektro series, which was never brought to operational service. The Elektro-L satellites are based on Lavochkins Navigator-Bus. Elektro-L also features receivers for the SARSAT-COSPAS emergency call system.
Rocket 586: Launch consisted of 53 Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2)
Rocket 587: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 588: Launch consisted of 56 Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2). Heaviest payload launched by Falcon 9 to date at 17.4 metric tons.
Rocket 589: The IGS-Radar 7 is a Japanese radar reconnaissance satellite. The satellite is operated by the Cabinet Satellite Information Center. The satellite serves both Japan's national defense and civil natural disaster monitoring.
Rocket 590: Rocket Lab and Electron's first launch from the United States, Virginia, and Wallops.
Rocket 591: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 592: GPS III (Global Positioning System) is the first evolution of the third generation of GPS satellites. The U.S. Air Force announced in May 2008 that a team led by Lockheed Martin had won the competition to build the next-generation Global Positioning System (Navstar) Space System program, known as GPS III.
Rocket 593: Continuous Broadcast Augmenting SATCOM 2 (CBAS-2) is a military communication satellite for the United States Space Force, which was reported to utilize space-based satellite relay links for augmenting existing communication links coverage for the USSF.
Rocket 594: 6 new satellites for the Jilin-1 commercial Earth observation satellite constellation.
Rocket 596: APStar 6E is a small high-throughput communication satellite for Hong Kong-based APT Satellite. It is based on the new DFH-3E small GEO platform developed by the China Academy of Space Technology (CAST), featuring all-electric propulsion. The satellite will provide satellite telecommunication services in the Asia-Pacific region.
Rocket 597: First flight of RS1 rocket and of ABL Space Systems.
Rocket 598: The 16th flight dedicated to the OneWeb high-speed Internet constellation. The initial constellation consists of 648 satellites. Later, the constellation could be expanded to more than 900 satellites depending on demand. OneWeb is expected to begin customer demonstrations in 2022, then provide a global, 24-hour service in 2022/2023.
Rocket 599: 2nd stage engine failure at ~17000 km/h after 2nd stage fuel filter within the fuel feedline was dislodged from its normal position, causing lower than usual fuel flow and subsequent rise in engine combustion chamber temperature.
Rocket 600: 5 different satellites on a ride share launch mission, details TBD.
Rocket 601: Possible experimental Chinese High-throughput communication satellite based on the DFH-4E satellite bus; details TBD.
Rocket 602: Transporter 6 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $275,000 per mission, which includes up to 50kg of payload mass.
Rocket 603: Israeli Earth Observation satellite with 38 cm resolution in panchromatic mode and 76 cm resolution in multi-spectral mode, covering a swath of ~12.5 km.
Rocket 604: Satellite official declared for spatial environment monitoring and in-orbit technical validation purposes. First satellite is observed to have entered a Molniya orbit.
Rocket 605: Launch consisted of 54 Starlink v1.5 satellites deployed into Starlink's second generation constellation (Starlink Gen 2). First launch dedicated to Starlink Gen 2
Rocket 606: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program "China High-definition Earth Observation System", alias CHEOS.
Rocket 608: First time a Falcon 9 booster was flown for the 15th time.
Rocket 609: The O3b mPower satellites are improved second generation satellites for the SES owned O3b Networks.
Rocket 610: The Surface Water Ocean Topography (SWOT) Mission is a future satellite mission, jointly developed by NASA and CNES, the French space agency, in partnership with Canadian Space Agency (CSA) and UK Space Agency (UKSA). The objectives of the mission are to make the first global survey of the Earth's surface water, observe the fine details of the ocean's surface topography, and measure how terrestrial surface water bodies change over time.
Rocket 611: Chinese classified satellite of unknown purposes.
Rocket 613: Second-stage vernier engines unexpectedly shut down during second stage main engine cut-off after LOX pump casing was broken by SECO-induced forces at the LOX inlet; the vernier engines were planned to continue firing to reach orbit.
Rocket 615: Chinese classified satellites of unknown purposes.
Rocket 616: HAKUTO-R is a multinational commercial lunar exploration program operated by ispace. It includes ispace's first two lunar missions, the first mission will perform a soft landing on the Moon in 2023. It will be the first private sector-led Japanese mission to land on the lunar surface.
Rocket 618: First Falcon 9 launch of OneWeb satellites.
Rocket 619: Gaofen-5-01A is a hyperspectral Earth observation satellite. Instruments include a 1500 km swath width Infrared imager, a 2.5nm spectral-resolution visible-near infrared hyperspectral imager & a differential absorption spectrometer for measuring atmospheric trace gas.
Rocket 620: Return to flight of the Kuaizhou 11 after its failed first launch.
Rocket 622: Shenzhou 15 (Chinese: 神舟十五号), marked the 10th crewed Chinese spaceflight and the fifteenth flight of the Shenzhou program. The spacecraft carried three People's Liberation Army Astronaut Corps (PLAAC) taikonauts on the fourth flight to the Tianhe core module, the first module of the Tiangong space station. The crew was composed of taikonauts Zhang Lu, Deng Qingming, and Fei Junlong.
Rocket 623: Last GLONASS-M satellite, after 47 previous satellites launched.
Rocket 625: SpaceX CRS-26 is a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. The mission is contracted by NASA and will be flown by SpaceX using a Cargo Dragon. This mission will deliver the second pair of iROSA solar arrays, which will be used to provide additional power to the station.
Rocket 626: EOS-06, also named Oceansat-3, is an Indian satellite designed to provide service continuity for operational users of the Ocean Colour Monitor (OCM) instrument on Oceansat-2. It will also enhance the potential of applications in other areas. The main objectives of OceanSat-3 are to study surface winds and ocean surface strata, observation of chlorophyll concentrations, monitoring of phytoplankton blooms, and study atmospheric aerosols and suspended sediments in the water.
Rocket 627: Eutelsat 10B is a planned all-electric communications satellite built by Thales Alenia Space on the Spacebus-Neo-200 platform for Eutelsat Communications to provide inflight and maritime connectivity at 10° East.
Rocket 628: The first flight of the Space Launch System (SLS). With more thrust at liftoff than the Saturn V, SLS became the most powerful rocket to ever reach orbit.
Rocket 629: 5 new Earth observation satellites for the Jilin-1 commercial Earth observation satellites constellation.
Rocket 630: Yaogan 34 is an optical remote sensing satellite, with a ground image resolution of a few meters, mainly used for land census, urban planning, land rights, road network design, crop yield estimation, and disaster prevention and mitigation. It was built by SAST.
Rocket 631: Intelsat's Galaxy 31 & 32 satellites will operate in the upper portion of the C-band spectrum, a range of wireless radio frequencies that is used for critical telecommunications and data connectivity around the world. With this mission, Intelsat will meet the accelerated C-band spectrum clearing timelines established by the U.S. Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
Rocket 632: The Tianzhou (Chinese: 天舟; lit. 'Heavenly Ship') is a Chinese automated cargo spacecraft developed from China's first prototype space station Tiangong-1 to resupply its future modular space station. It was first launched (Tianzhou 1) on the Long March 7 rocket on April 20, 2017, and demonstrated autonomous propellant transfer (space refueling).
Rocket 633: Chinese satellite reported for atmospheric/ocean/environmental/spatial parameter research purposes, details TBD.
Rocket 634: JPSS-2, or Joint Polar Satellite System-2, is the second of the United States National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's latest generation of U.S. polar-orbiting, non-geosynchronous, environmental satellites called the Joint Polar Satellite System. JPSS-2 will join NOAA-20 the Suomi National Polar-orbiting Partnership satellite in the same orbit. Circling the Earth from pole-to-pole, it will cross the equator about 14 times daily, providing full global coverage twice a day.
Rocket 635: Cygnus NG-18 (Northrop Grumman-18) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.
Rocket 636: ChinaSat 19 (Zhongxing 19) is a Chinese high throughput (HTS) Ka-band communications satellite based on the DFH-4E satellite bus for serving China-US air routes.
Rocket 637: The first stage was planned to be recovered by helicopter, but the mid-air catch attempt was canceled due to unstable telemetry from the 1st stage during re-entry.
Rocket 638: Two soccer balls for the 2022 World Cup were flown aboard the first stage as a suborbital payload, reaching a max altitude of 123 km.
Rocket 639: The Tundra or EKS (Edinaya Kosmicheskaya Sistema) series of satellites is the next generation of Russian early warning satellites to replace the US-K and US-KMO early warning satellites of the Oko-1 system.
Rocket 640: First SpaceX mission direct to GEO.
Rocket 641: The Laboratory Cabin Modules (LCM)s are a major element of the Chinese space station, based on Tiangong-2, as the final stage of Project 921 Tiangong, part of the Chinese space program. While China's small unmanned spacecraft can provide platforms for zero gravity and exposure to space for scientific research, the LCMs offer a long-term environment combined with ready access by human researchers over periods that far exceed the capabilities of Shenzhou spacecraft. Operations will be controlled from the Beijing Aerospace Command and Control Center in the People's Republic of China.
Rocket 642: Chinese classified satellite of unknown purposes.
Rocket 643: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 644: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-21 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 174th flight of a Progress.
Rocket 645: Goniets is a Russian civilian low Earth orbit communication satellite system. It consists of a number of satellites, derived from Strela military communication satellites. Goniets-M are upgraded versions of the Goniets satellites, a civilian derivate of the military Strela-3 satellite system. They are operated in the Goniets-D1M constellation. The Goniets system was offered to support international health organizations to meet their global communications needs for the transfer of medical data and records to remote sites.
Rocket 646: First commercial mission by GSLV MK III. First non-Soyuz OneWeb launch.
Rocket 647: 2 classified satellites for the Russian military.
Rocket 648: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 649: Rumoured to be EMKA-3, a Russian reconnaissance satellite.
Rocket 650: Hotbird 13F and 13G are two high power direct to home communications satellites to replace Hotbird 8, 9 and 10 at Eutelsats's 13° East position.
Rocket 652: Chinese S-Band Synthetic Aperture Radar satellite with 5 m resolution.
Rocket 653: Angosat-2 is a replacement for the Angosat-1 telecommunications satellite which failed in orbit.
Rocket 654: Flight Termination System activated at T+06:28 after rocket was observed not in correct attitude for normal 2nd/3rd stage separation, due to 1 set of 2 RCS thrusters on the 2nd stage motor failing to pressurize, in turn caused by a leak in the diaphragm joint between the helium and hydrazine sides of the RCS fuel tank.
Rocket 655: GLONASS-K is the latest satellite design intended as a part of the Russian GLONASS radio-based satellite navigation system. Developed by ISS Reshetnev (Reshetnev Information Satellite Systems) and first launched on 26 February 2011, it is a substantial improvement of the previous GLONASS-M second-generation satellites, having a longer lifespan and better accuracy.
Rocket 656: ASO-S (Advanced Space-borne Solar Observatory) is a Chinese solar space observatory that aims to study the interaction between the Sun's magnetic field, solar flares, and coronal mass ejections. It's the first space solar observatory of China.
Rocket 657: Intelsat's Galaxy 33 & 34 satellites will operate in the upper portion of the C-band spectrum, a range of wireless radio frequencies that is used for critical telecommunications and data connectivity around the world. With this mission, Intelsat will meet the accelerated C-band spectrum clearing timelines established by the U.S. Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
Rocket 658: The Argos-4 payload on board the GAzelle satellite is part of the international Argos program that collects data from thousands of sensors and transmitters located around the world. Argos data is collected and distributed for use in numerous applications, and helps provide a better understanding of Earth’s physical and biological environment, including its weather and climate, biodiversity and ecosystems, as well as assist with maritime security, offshore pollution, and humanitarian assistance. Information gathered via the Argos system also enables industries to comply with environmental protection regulations. Argos has most famously been used to track wildlife, particularly marine mammals and sea turtles since the 1980s. There are currently 22,000 active transmitters around the world that the Argos system is monitoring, with almost 7,800 tracking wildlife.
Rocket 659: CentiSpace-1 S5 and S6 are Chinese commercial small satellites by Beijing-based company Future Navigation for providing GNSS augmentation signals services from LEO. They are precursors to a planned 160 satellites constellation.
Rocket 660: Launched 7 hours and 10 minutes after Crew-5 from Florida, marking SpaceX's shortest period between two launches as of liftoff, and cutting SpaceX's record in half.
Rocket 661: SpaceX Crew-5 is the fifth operational crewed rotation mission of a Crew Dragon spacecraft to the International Space Station. The crew will consist of commander Nicole Aunapu Mann (NASA), pilot Josh Cassada (NASA), and mission specialists Koichi Wakata (JAXA) and Anna Kikina (Roscosmos).
Rocket 662: These satellites will enable SES to clear 280MHz of mid-band spectrum for 5G use while seamlessly migrating SES’s existing C-band customers and ensuring the continued delivery of digital television to nearly 120 million American TV homes and other critical data services.
Rocket 663: Second demonstration flight of Firefly Alpha. Firefly was able to achieve orbit for the first time, however, the educational payloads on-board were deployed in a lower orbit than expected.
Rocket 666: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 668: Final launch of Delta IV Heavy rocket from VSFB.
Rocket 669:
Soyuz MS-22 is a crewed mission to the International Space Station.
The crew consists of commander Sergey Prokopyev (Roscosmos) and flight engineers Dmitry Petelin (Roscosmos) and Francisco Rubio (NASA).
Rocket 670: Yunhai-1 is a series of Chinese meteorological satellites built by the Shanghai Academy of Spaceflight Technology (SAST).
Rocket 671: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 672: The Owl Spreads Its Wings mission is the second of a bulk buy of three Electron launches by Synspective to deliver their StriX satellites to low Earth orbit. StriX-1 is Synspective’s first commercial satellite for its synthetic aperture radar (SAR) satellite constellation to deliver imagery that can detect millimeter-level changes to the Earth’s surface from space, independent of weather conditions on Earth and at any time of the day or night. “The Owl Spreads Its Wings” will be Rocket Lab’s third mission for Synspective after successful launches in December 2020 and February 2022.
Rocket 673: Note: provisional information based on satellite naming
Rocket 674: BE-3 booster engine shutdown at T+1:05 after engine nozzle suffered thermo-structural failure, caused by recent design changes made to the engine’s boundary layer cooling system. Launch escape system was activated and the capsule landed nominally.
Rocket 675: With this launch, B1058 became the first Falcon 9 booster to launch 14 times.
Rocket 678: CentiSpace-1 S3 and S4 are Chinese commercial small satellites by Beijing-based company Future Navigation for providing GNSS augmentation signals services from LEO. They are precursors to a planned 160 satellites constellation.
Rocket 679: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 680: The Yaogan 33-02 is a Chinese military “remote sensing” satellite of unknown purpose.
Rocket 681: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 682: First launch of 54 Starlink v1.5 satellites. Heaviest payload launched to date by Falcon 9 at 16.7 metric tons. Fastest turnaround of droneship ASOG to date, at 8 days and around 8 hours, beating its previous record by about 17 hours.
Rocket 683: 0.5 m resolution Earth observation satellite for Twenty First Century Aerospace Technology Company Ltd.
Rocket 684: Satellites of unknown purposes built by the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
Rocket 685: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 687: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 688: 16 new Earth observation satellites for the Jilin-1 commercial Earth observation satellites constellation.
Rocket 689: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 690: Khayyam, also known as Project 505, is a Russian-built Earth observation satellite for Iran. The satellite is built by VNIIEM and NPK Barl on a currently unidentified satellite bus, with a resolution reaching < 1 m.
Rocket 691: With this launch, Galactic Energy became the first private launch provider to succeed in all three of its first launches.
Rocket 693: The Korea Aerospace Research Institute (KARI) signed a lunar exploration technical cooperation with NASA which increased the possibility of exploration success greatly. A Korean Pathfinder Lunar Orbiter (KPLO) is to be followed by a Korean Lunar Explorer (KLE) which consists of an orbiter and a lander unit equipped with a small rover with a mass of approximately 20 kg. The key goals of the Korean lunar mission are the investigations of lunar geology and space environment, exploration of lunar resources, and testing of future space and planetary exploration technology which will assist in future human activities on the moon and beyond.
Rocket 694: Launch time is approximate. After spending 276 days in orbit, the CSSHQ returned to Earth on 8 May 2023.
Rocket 695: Coby Cotton, Mário Ferreira, Vanessa O’Brien, Clint Kelly, Sara Sabry, and Steve Young flew aboard New Shepard.
Rocket 696: The Space-Based Infrared System (SBIRS) is a consolidated system intended to meet the United States' infrared space surveillance needs through the first two to three decades of the 21st century. The SBIRS program is designed to provide key capabilities in the areas of missile warning, missile defense and battlespace characterization via satellites in geosynchronous earth orbit (GEO), sensors hosted on satellites in highly elliptical orbit (HEO), and ground-based data processing and control. SBIRS ground software integrates infrared sensor programs of the U.S. Air Force (USAF) with new IR sensors.
Rocket 697: NROL-199 is a classified mission for the National Reconnaissance Office.
Rocket 698: The Terrestrial Ecosystem Carbon Monitoring Satellite (TECIS) is intended to evaluate forest biomass, measure atmospheric aerosol content, and detect photosynthetic fluorescence. These measurements will contribute to efforts to combat global warming.
Rocket 699: Reported to be Russian military "inspector satellites" (14F150 Nivelir) for orbital surveillance, suspected to be similar to Cosmos 2519/20 & 2542/3
Rocket 701: First flight of Zhongke-1A. First flight of a launcher developed by the CAS (Chinese Academy of Sciences).
Rocket 702: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 703: The Laboratory Cabin Modules (LCM)s are a major element of the Chinese space station, based on Tiangong-2, as the final stage of Project 921 Tiangong, part of the Chinese space program. While China's small unmanned spacecraft can provide platforms for zero gravity and exposure to space for scientific research, the LCMs offer a long-term environment combined with ready access by human researchers over periods that far exceed the capabilities of Shenzhou spacecraft. Operations will be controlled by the Beijing Aerospace Command and Control Center in the People's Republic of China.
Rocket 704: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 705: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 706: Commercial Earth observation satellites built by CAST for China Siwei Survey and Mapping Technology Co. Ltd.
Rocket 707: SpaceX CRS-25 is a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. The mission is contracted by NASA and will be flown by SpaceX using a Cargo Dragon.
Rocket 708: First flight of Vega C. This flight was managed by ESA. Flight VV21.
Rocket 709: NROL-162 is a classified mission for the National Reconnaissance Office.
Rocket 710: The TL 2 (Tian Lian 2) satellite is a geostationary relay satellite based on the DFH-4 Bus (three-axis-stabilized telecommunications satellite platform).
Rocket 711: First launch of Starlink satellites to the third orbital shell.
Rocket 712: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 713: GLONASS-K (Russian: Глобальная навигационная спутниковая система, "Global Navigation Satellite System") is the latest satellite design intended as a part of the Russian GLONASS radio-based satellite navigation system. Developed by ISS Reshetnev (Information Satellite Systems Reshetnev) and first launched on 26 February 2011, it is a substantial improvement of the previous GLONASS-M second-generation satellites, having a longer lifespan and better accuracy.
Rocket 714: STP-S28 is a complex mission that will deliver a number of technology demonstrations to orbit, such as Space Domain Awareness and communications advancement, and inform future space system development.
Rocket 715: Wide Field of View (WFOV) is a testbed spacecraft that informs the Next Gen Overhead Persistent Infrared program (OPIR). The Next Gen OPIR program will succeed the Space Based Infrared Systems program and is designed to provide a resilient space-based global missile warning capability against emerging missile and counter-space threats.
Rocket 717: This satellite will enable SES to clear 280MHz of mid-band spectrum for 5G use while seamlessly migrating SES’s existing C-band customers and ensuring the continued delivery of digital television to nearly 120 million American TV homes and other critical data services.
Rocket 718: Longest Rocket Lab mission to date. Time between launch and CAPSTONE deployment was just under 6 days.
Rocket 719: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program China High-definition Earth Observation System (CHEOS).
Rocket 724: Second flight of KSLV-2 and first flight of this rocket with payloads.
Rocket 725: Launched around 14 hours after SARah 1 from California, marking SpaceX's shortest period between two launches as of liftoff, and passing the previous record by about an hour.
Rocket 726: SARah 1 is a phased array radar satellite built by Airbus. It is part of the three satellite constellation being built for the German government as a follow-up to the SAR-Lupe radar sat constellation.
Rocket 727: 50th SpaceX launch from LC-39A. With this launch, B1060 became the first Falcon 9 booster to launch 13 times.
Rocket 728: Second stage engine suffered a premature cutoff, leaving the payloads in a suborbital trajectory ~1km/s short of the intended orbit.
Rocket 729: Egyptian satellite operator Nilesat has partnered with SpaceX for the launch of Nilesat-301 geostationary communications satellite. The satellite is based on the Spacebus 4000-B2 platform and will weigh about four metric tons at launch. It offers a design life exceeding 15 years.
Rocket 730: Shenzhou 14 (Chinese: 神舟十四号) is the flight that marked the ninth crewed Chinese spaceflight and the fourteenth flight of the Shenzhou program. The spacecraft carried three People's Liberation Army Astronaut Corps (PLAAC) taikonauts on the third flight to the Tianhe core module, the first module of the Tiangong space station. The crew on this mission were taikonauts Cai Xuzhe, Chen Dong, and Liu Yang.
Rocket 731: First time a paying customer flies for a second time on New Shepard.
Rocket 732: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-20 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 173rd flight of a Progress.
Rocket 733: LEO communications satellites for Chinese car manufacturer Geely Automotive for testing autonomous driving/inter-vehicle communication services. They also carry payloads for ocean observation.
Rocket 734: Transporter 5 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $1 million per mission, which includes up to 200 kg of payload mass.
Rocket 735: "Ronghe Shiyan Weixing" (RSW) = "Integrated Experimental Satellite" are test satellites that will be used to develop a state-owned Chinese low-earth orbit constellation, Xingwang, consisting of several thousand satellites.
Rocket 736: Redo of the Orbital Flight Test after Starliner experienced numerous problems on its first orbital spaceflight.
Rocket 738: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 739: SpaceX launched another batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 740: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 741: Blockage of the fuel main valve on the rocket's 2000N thrust RCS system caused RCS fuel to leak and be used up too early. Subsequently during 3rd stage burn vehicle went out of attitude control & self-destructed.
Rocket 742: The Tianzhou (Chinese: 天舟; lit. 'Heavenly Ship') is a Chinese automated cargo spacecraft developed from China's first prototype space station Tiangong-1 to resupply its future modular space station. It was first launched (Tianzhou 1) on the Long March 7 rocket on April 20, 2017, and demonstrated autonomous propellant transfer (space refueling).
Rocket 743: Fastest turnaround of droneship ASOG to date, at 9 days and around 2 hours, beating its previous record by about 3 days.
Rocket 744: Earth observation satellites for the Jilin-1 commercial Earth observation satellites constellation.
Rocket 745: For the first time, Rocket Lab attempted a mid air recovery of an Electron booster. While the booster was caught, the helicopter pilot experienced unexpected forces and made the decision to cut the line the booster was hanging from. It splashed down and was recovered by Rocket Lab's recovery ship.
Rocket 746: Earth observation satellites for the Jilin-1 commercial Earth observation satellites constellation.
Rocket 747: Fastest Falcon 9 booster turnaround to date at 21 days and 6 hours, beating the 27 days and 4 hours record previously held by B1060. Additionally, this is the fastest droneship turnaround to date at 8 days and 3 hours, beating the previous record by about 3 hours, and was the first time JRTI held the droneship turnaround record.
Rocket 749: Commercial Earth observation satellites built by CAST for China Siwei Survey and Mapping Technology Co. Ltd., with resolution down to 0.5 meters.
Rocket 750: SpaceX Crew-4 is the fourth operational crewed rotation mission of a Crew Dragon spacecraft to the International Space Station. NASA astronauts Kjell Lindgren and Bob Hines will serve as spacecraft commander and pilot, respectively, for the Crew-4 mission. NASA astronaut Jessica Watkins and ESA astronaut Samantha Cristoforetti will serve as mission specialists.
Rocket 751: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 752: NOSS-3 (Naval Ocean Surveillance System), which is likely not the official designation, is the third generation of NOSS satellites, which are low orbit SIGINT satellites. In 2013, the designation Intruder leaked out. These satellites carry equipment to track ships and aircraft via their radio transmissions. Positions of the origin of the transmissions are determined by triangulation.
Rocket 753: China’s first satellite dedicated to comprehensive monitoring of the atmospheric environment, named Daqi-1, also known as Atmospheric Environment Monitoring Satellite (AEMS) and developed by the Shanghai Academy of Spaceflight Technology (SAST) in Shanghai, is designed to operate in sun-synchronous orbit. Daqi-1 can monitor fine particle pollution like PM2.5, pollutant gases including nitrogen dioxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, as well as carbon dioxide concentration.
Rocket 754: ZX 6D (Zhongxing 6D, ChinaSat 6D) is a Chinese communications satellite based on a DFH-4 bus. It is similar to ZX 6C launched in 2019.
Rocket 755: Axiom signed a contract with SpaceX for a Crew Dragon flight piloted by former NASA astronaut Michael López-Alegría. Investors Larry Connor, Mark Pathy, and Eytan Stibbe flew as customers on the mission.
Rocket 757: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program China High-definition Earth Observation System (CHEOS).
Rocket 758: BlackSky 16 and 17 are part of sixty high-resolution Earth observation microsatellites in the BlackSky constellation. This constellation will provide real-time earth observation. the constellation is built by Blacksky, a SpaceFlight Subsidiary, and the satellites are produced by LeoStella LLC, a joint venture of Spaceflight Industries and Thales Alenia Space.
Rocket 759: Transporter 4 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $1 million per mission, which includes up to 200 kg of payload mass.
Rocket 760: Marty Allen, Sharon and Marc Hagle, Jim Kitchen, Dr. George Nield, and Gary Lai flew aboard New Shepard. Gary Lai was the Senior Director and Chief Architect of the New Shepard launch system, and one of Blue Origin's 20 founding employees. He was invited as a guest and did not pay for the flight.
Rocket 761: The Tianping-2 A/B/C satellites were built by the China Aerospace Science and Industry Corporation (CASIC) and will be used to provide services such as atmospheric space environment study and orbital prediction model correction.
Rocket 762: First flight of Long March 6A. First Chinese rocket to use solid boosters.
Rocket 763: It is the 10th Meridian satellite to fly. It's named 20L because ISS Rechetnyov (manufacturer) numbering system starts from 11. The letter L is added to indicate that it is a flight unit (лётный in Russian).
Rocket 764: First time a Falcon 9 booster flew for the 12th time.
Rocket 765: First all-Roscosmos flight to the ISS.
Rocket 766: Yaogan 34 is an optical remote sensing satellite, with a ground image resolution of a few meters, mainly used for land census, urban planning, land rights, road network design, crop yield estimation, and disaster prevention and mitigation. It was built by SAST.
Rocket 768: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 769: Nour 2 (also transliterated Noor 2) is the first indigenous Iranian military satellite, operated by the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC). No details are known. The satellite is built to the 6U CubeSat form factor. According to an interview with the IRGC Air Force Space Commander, the satellite has an imaging mission.
Rocket 770: The first flight dedicated to the launch of the Internet constellation of GalaxySpace, a private company, planning the total deployment of more than 1000 satellites in earth orbit. The satellites broadcast in 5G, with a capacity of 10 Gb.
Rocket 771: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 772: GOES-T is the third of the next generation of weather satellites operated by NOAA, giving sequence to the GOES system. The GOES-R Series (including GOES-R, -S, -T, and -U) provides advanced imagery and atmospheric measurements of Earth’s weather, oceans, and environment, real-time mapping of total lightning activity, and improved monitoring of solar activity and space weather.
Rocket 773: StriX β is a Japanese synthetic aperture radar satellite built by Synspective as a demonstrator for their planned 25-satellite constellation. It will feature an X-band synthetic aperture radar.
Rocket 774: The Spacety company launched the first satellites of its Tianxian SAR constellation.
Rocket 775: L-SAR 01B (Ludi Tance-1 01B) is a Chinese satellite equipped with a synthetic aperture radar (SAR). It operates in differential interferometry in L-band, within a group of two satellites operating in quasi-heliosynchronous orbit.
Rocket 776: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 777: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 778: Cygnus NG-17 (Northrop Grumman-17) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.
Rocket 779: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-19 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 172nd flight of a Progress.
Rocket 780: EOS-04, also named RISAT (Radar Imaging Satellite), is a series of Indian radar imaging reconnaissance satellites built by ISRO. They provide all-weather surveillance using synthetic aperture radars (SAR).
Rocket 781:
LV0008. First launch of Rocket 3 from Cape Canaveral.
Incorrectly connected wires resulted in the payload fairing failing to separate prior to stage separation; the second stage then spun out of control after striking the fairing. This was compounded by a software issue on the upper stage, which resulted in the loss of thrust vector control (TVC).
Rocket 782: The 13th flight dedicated to the OneWeb high-speed Internet constellation. The initial constellation consists of 648 satellites, launched by 20 Soyuz from 3 different countries (France, Kazakhstan, and Russia). Later, the constellation could be expanded to more than 900 satellites depending on demand. OneWeb is expected to begin customer demonstrations in 2022, then provide a global, 24-hour service in 2022/2023.
Rocket 783: Cosmos 2553 is possibly the Neitron satellite, which is a Russian military reconnaissance satellite designed by NPO Mashinostroyeniya on the Kondor platform, which would be a satellite designed to carry out optical reconnaissance on the ground, but also to take precise photographs of payloads in orbit.
Rocket 784: According to SpaceX, up to 40 of the 49 satellites launched will, or already have, reentered the atmosphere just a few days after launch. Due to the failures being related to a geomagnetic storm and not the Falcon 9 launch vehicle, the mission is still a success.
Rocket 785: A classified payload for the National Reconnaissance Office.
Rocket 786: First time a Falcon 9 was built and flown as a Falcon Heavy side core then converted to a standard Falcon 9.
Rocket 787: L-SAR 01A (Ludi Tance-1 01A) is a Chinese satellite equipped with a synthetic aperture radar (SAR). It operates in differential interferometry in L-band, within a group of two satellites operating in quasi-heliosynchronous orbit.
Rocket 788: First and only flight of Atlas V 511.
Rocket 789: Fastest turnaround of droneship ASOG to date, at 12 days and around 4 hours, beating its previous record by about 4 days.
Rocket 791:
The PAN (Pathfinder for Autonomous Navigation) is a technology demonstration series of satellite aimed to test autonomous docking operations between CubeSats.
The form factor is a 3U CubeSat and are probably the most complex CubeSats ever made to date, they will test new algorithms for rendezvous and docking as well as new magnetic docking technology and new GPS-based docking systems that could lead to a simplification of standard docking hardware.
Rocket 792: Transporter 3 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $1 million per mission, which includes up to 200 kg of payload mass.
Rocket 793: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 794: The Iranian authorities announced this flight as successful, and suborbital. However, the trajectory of the launcher, very close to having made an orbit, suggests rather that it is a failed attempt to reach low Earth orbit.
Rocket 795: Chinese classified satellite claimed to be for communication technology test purposes. Actual mission not known.
Rocket 797: First flight of the Persey upper stage. Last of the three demonstration flights planned. Upper stage failed to restart for 2nd burn leaving upper stage & payload in LEO.
Rocket 799: ZY-1 02E is a Chinese Earth observation satellite. The primary objective is to acquire high-resolution panchromatic and multispectral imagery for land resource surveys, disaster monitoring, forestry, and ecological monitoring.
Rocket 800: Flight VA256. The launch is funded by ESA in exchange for science time on the telescope from NASA.
Rocket 802: Inmarsat-6 F1 is a communications satellite to be operated by the British satellite operator Inmarsat and designed and manufactured by Airbus Defence and Space on the Eurostar 3000EOR platform. Part of the I-6 satellite fleet, it will be Inmarsat's first dual-payload satellite, with capabilities in both L-band and Ka band.
Rocket 803: Falcon Booster B1069 successfully landed on the drone ship Just Read the Instructions, however, damage to the landing legs as well as the Merlin Engines was observed when the booster returned to port. This damage was likely caused by the Octograbber, which remotely secures the booster after landing.
Rocket 804: Launched only 15 hours after Starlink Group 4-4 from California, marking the first time SpaceX launched twice within 24 hours.
Rocket 805: With this launch, B1051 became the first Falcon 9 booster to launch 11 times.
Rocket 806: First launch of commercial navigation satellites. The launch failed for an unknown reason.
Rocket 807: The TL 2 (Tian Lian 2) satellite is a geostationary relay satellite based on the DFH-4 Bus (three-axis-stabilized telecommunications satellite platform).
Rocket 808: The final of 5 burns by the Briz-M upper stage was cut short, leaving the payloads in a lower-than-intended orbit.
Rocket 809: Michael Strahan, Laura Shepard Churchley, Dylan Taylor, Evan Dick, Lane Bess, and Cameron Bess flew aboard New Shepard. Laura is the daughter of Alan Shepard, the first American to reach space and the namesake of the New Shepard rocket. Her father's flight was similar to hers — a suborbital flight.
Rocket 810: The SJ 6 (Shi Jian 6) series consisted of pairs of technology satellites, which were reported to be used to probe the space environment, radiation, and its effects, record space physical environment parameters, and conduct other related space experiments.
Rocket 811: The Imaging X-ray Polarimetry Explorer (IXPE) is a space observatory with three identical telescopes designed to measure the polarization of cosmic X-rays. The mission will study exotic astronomical objects and permit mapping of the magnetic fields of black holes, neutron stars, pulsars, supernova remnants, magnetars, quasars, and active galactic nuclei. The high-energy X-ray radiation from these objects' surrounding environment can be polarized – vibrating in a particular direction. Studying the polarization of X-rays reveals the physics of these objects and can provide insights into the high-temperature environments where they are created.
Rocket 812: BlackSky Global 16 and 17 are part of sixty high resolution earth observation microsatellites in the BlackSky constellation. This constellation will provide real-time earth observation. the constellation is built by Blacksky, a SpaceFlight Subsidiary, and the satellites are produced by LeoStella LLC, a joint venture of Spaceflight Industries and Thales Alenia Space.
Rocket 813: First Japanese tourist in space. First Soyuz tourist flight in 10 years.
Rocket 814: STPSat-6 is an advanced satellite for national security and science missions that delivers operational NUclear DETonation (NUDET) detection capabilities, high-bandwidth laser communications services, and new technology demonstrations in space domain awareness, weather, and NUDET detection. STPSat-6‘s nine payloads include the NNSA’s (National Nuclear Security Administration) Space and Atmospheric Burst Reporting System (SABRS), NASA’s Laser communications Relay Demonstration (LCRD), and seven Space Experiments Review Board (SERB) payloads that demonstrate cutting edge space technologies.
Rocket 815: The Golden Bauhinia 1-03 satellite is mainly used to verify the technology of satellite remote sensing platforms.
Rocket 817: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 818: The FH 2 (Feng Huo 2) series are reportedly the second generation of Chinese military comsats and data relay satellites. They provide both C-band and UHF communications.
Rocket 819: The Tundra or EKS (Edinaya Kosmicheskaya Sistema) series of satellites is the next generation of Russian early warning satellites to replace the US-K and US-KMO early warning satellites of the Oko-1 system.
Rocket 820: Unknown Chinese satellite reportedly for technology development purposes.
Rocket 821: First flight of Progress on Soyuz 2.1b. Last flight of Progress-M.
Rocket 822: The Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) mission is the first-ever mission to demonstrate the capability to deflect an asteroid by colliding a spacecraft with it at high speed – a technique known as a kinetic impactor.
Rocket 823: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program China High-definition Earth Observation System (CHEOS).
Rocket 825: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program "China High-definition Earth Observation System", alias CHEOS.
Rocket 826: BlackSky’s Global 14 and 15 are part of sixty high resolution earth observation microsatellites in the BlackSky constellation. This constellation will provide real-time earth observation. the constellation is built by Blacksky, a SpaceFlight Subsidiary, and the satellites are produced by LeoStella LLC, a joint venture of Spaceflight Industries and Thales Alenia Space.
Rocket 828: First launch of Starlink satellites to the fourth orbital shell.
Rocket 829: SpaceX Crew-3 is the third operational crew rotation mission to the International Space Station using a Crew Dragon spacecraft. It will feature NASA astronauts Raja Chari, Thomas Marshburn, and Kayla Barron along with ESA astronaut Matthias Maurer.
Rocket 830: RAISE-2 (RApid Innovative payload demonstration Satellite-2) is a satellite for on-orbit demonstrations of six demonstration components and equipment selected by public solicitation. The satellite will be operated in response to requests from the demonstration theme proposers, and will provide experimental data of the demonstration devices and environmental data during the experiments.
Rocket 832: Satellite developed by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) for pursuing sustainable development.
Rocket 833: The Yaogan 32-02-01 and 32-02-02 are Chinese military satellites of unknown purpose.
Rocket 834: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-18 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 171st flight of a Progress.
Rocket 835: Jilin 1 satellites are a series of Chinese commercial remote sensing satellites for high-definition video within the Jilin-1 constellation designed and owned by the Chang Guang Satellite Technology Co.
Rocket 839: First flight of KSLV-2. First flight of an entirely South Korean launcher.
Rocket 840: Lucy is a NASA space probe that will tour five Jupiter trojans, asteroids that share Jupiter's orbit around the Sun, orbiting either ahead of or behind the planet. All will be fly-by missions. Three instruments comprise the payload: a high-resolution visible imager, an optical and near-infrared imaging spectrometer, and a thermal infrared spectrometer.
Rocket 841: Shenzhou 13 (Chinese: 神舟十三号) was a Chinese spaceflight launched on 15 October 2021 at 16:23 UTC. The flight marked the eighth crewed Chinese spaceflight and the thirteenth flight of the Shenzhou program. The spacecraft carried three People's Liberation Army Astronaut Corps (PLAAC) taikonauts on the second flight to the Tianhe core module, the first module of the Tiangong space station. The launch of the three-person crew with a Long March-2F launch vehicle took place from the Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center.
Rocket 842: The Chinese Hα Solar Explorer (CHASE) is designed to test a newly developed satellite platform and conduct solar observations. The scientific payload of the satellite is an Hα imaging spectrograph (HIS), which can, for the first time, acquire full-disk spectroscopic solar observations in the Hα waveband.
Rocket 844: Chris Boshuizen, Glen de Vries, William Shatner, and Audrey Powers flew aboard New Shepard. William Shatner became the oldest person to date to travel into space, at 90 years old.
Rocket 845:
Soyuz MS-19 is a crewed mission to the International Space Station.
The crew is composed by the cosmonaut and mission commander Anton Shkaplerov and 2 tourists: Klim Shipenko and Yulia Peresild. They will use the time aboard the ISS to shoot some scenes of a movie called "The Challenge".
Rocket 846: Landsat 9 is an American Earth observation satellite. NASA is in charge of building, launching, and testing the system, while the United States Geological Survey (USGS) will process, archive, and distribute its data. It's intended as the eighth satellite in the Landsat series, Landsat 6 failed to reach orbit.
Rocket 847: The satellite suffered an anomaly during launch, but was rumoured - and subsequently observed via orbital changes - to have been recovered about a month after launch.
Rocket 848: The rocket is named "Peace Elite", from a Chinese video game, which sponsors this launch. The usernames of the players of the game will also be launched on this flight.
Rocket 849: The Tianzhou (Chinese: 天舟; lit. 'Heavenly Ship') is a Chinese automated cargo spacecraft developed from China's first prototype space station Tiangong-1 to resupply its modular space station. It was first launched (Tianzhou 1) on the Long March 7 rocket on April 20, 2017, and demonstrated autonomous propellant transfer (space refueling).
Rocket 850: Inspiration4 is the world’s first all-civilian mission to space, and the second fully private crewed spaceflight, after Soyuz TM-30 in 2000. The mission will be commanded by Jared Isaacman, the 37-year-old founder and Chief Executive Officer of Shift4 Payments and an accomplished pilot and adventurer. Inspiration4 will leave Earth from Kennedy Space Center’s historic Launch Complex 39A, the embarkation point for Apollo and Space Shuttle missions, and travel across a low earth orbit on a multi-day journey that will continually eclipse more than 90% of the earth’s population. Named in recognition of the four-person crew that will raise awareness and funds for St. Jude Children’s Research Hospital, this milestone represents a new era for human spaceflight and exploration, according to the company.
Rocket 852: First launch of Starlink satellites from Vandenberg SFB, and first launch to the second orbital shell.
Rocket 854: Zhongxing-9B is a Chinese communications satellite, that will replace the Zhongxing-9A satellite in orbit. The latter was launched in 2017, but the CZ-3B launch vehicle suffered a partial failure, and the satellite had to burn a large amount of fuel to reach its nominal orbit.
Rocket 855: Gaofen (GF) is a series of Chinese civilian remote sensing satellites for the state-sponsored program China High-definition Earth Observation System (CHEOS).
Rocket 856: The first flight of Firefly Alpha.
Rocket 857: First booster landing on A Shortfall of Gravitas, SpaceX's newest droneship. First reuse of a Cargo Dragon 2 capsule.
Rocket 858: LV0006. First launch of Rocket 3 with a customer payload. First Rocket 3 with stretched propellant tanks.
Rocket 859: New Shepard flew a NASA lunar landing technology demonstration for a second time on the exterior of the booster, 18 commercial payloads inside the crew capsule, 11 of which are NASA-supported, and an art installation on the exterior of the capsule.
Rocket 860: TJSW-7 is likely a Chinese early warning satellite.
Rocket 861: "Ronghe Shiyan Weixing" (RSW) = "Integrated Experimental Satellite" are test satellites that will be used to develop a state-owned Chinese low-earth orbit constellation, Xingwang, consisting of several thousand satellites.
Rocket 863: TH 2 (Tianhui-2 = "Sky drawing") is a Chinese series of cartography and Earth observation satellites.
Rocket 865: 3rd stage suffered insufficient pressure in the liquid hydrogen tank at engine start, due to vent and relief valve soft seal damage and leakage, which led to a failed engine ignition.
Rocket 866: Cygnus NG-16 (Northrop Grumman-16) is a cargo resupply mission of the Northrop Grumman Cygnus spacecraft to the International Space Station under the Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) contract with NASA.
Rocket 867: Chinese communication satellite. It would provide Ku-band communications and feature advanced multiple steerable spot beam antenna technology to allow ground users to communicate while traveling, as well as secure uplink transmission for satellite antenna control.
Rocket 868:
The KL-Beta A and B, satellites are test satellites for a global multimedia satellite system for the German company KLEO Connect.
The satellites were built by CAS Microspace and feature a Ka-band communications payload.
Rocket 869: Payload fairing failed to separate, due to the silicone rubber fitting stuck on the separation bolt access covers along the longitudinal separation plane.
Rocket 871:
Monolith is a USAF Research Laboratory technology demonstration satellite.
The microsatellite is set to demonstrate new deployable instruments in very small satellite bus. Monolith will carry a weather monitoring instrument.
Rocket 872: Tianhui 1 (TH-1) is a stereo-topographic mapping satellite developed by China SpaceSat Co. Ltd., a commercial branch of China Academy of Space Technology (CAST), with the development commencing in 2005. The satellite is similar in roles and capability to Ziyuan 3 but features a different electro-optical mission payload developed by the Changchun Institute of Optics, Fine Machinery, and Physics (CIOMP) of the China Academy of Sciences (CAS).
Rocket 873: First new module of the ISS since 2016 (BEAM). First flight of Proton-M without an upper stage.
Rocket 874: First time New Shepard launched astronauts to space.
Rocket 876: First fully crewed flight for SpaceShipTwo.
Rocket 877: The Ningxin-1 satellites (also called Zhongzi) are a series of Chinese commercial remote sensing satellites owned by Ningxia Jingui Information Technology Co. Ltd.
Rocket 878: Tianlian 1, also known as Tian Lian 1, TL-1, and CTDRS-1 is a Chinese data tracking and relay communications satellite series. Based on the DFH-3 satellite bus, it will provide communication coverage for manned Shenzhou missions, from Shenzhou 7 onwards. Functionally, it is similar to the United States Tracking and Data Relay Satellite System.
Rocket 879: The newer FY-3 series is an improved generation of polar-orbiting heliosynchronous weather satellites.
Rocket 880: Jilin 1 satellites are a series of Chinese commercial remote sensing satellites for high-definition video within the Jilin-1 constellation designed and owned by the Chang Guang Satellite Technology Co.
Rocket 882: Transporter 2 is a dedicated rideshare mission by SpaceX. SpaceX’s SmallSat Rideshare Program provides small satellite operators with regularly scheduled, dedicated Falcon 9 rideshare missions to SSO for ESPA class payloads for as low as $1 million per mission, which includes up to 200 kg of payload mass.
Rocket 883:
The Space Test Program (STP) is the primary provider of spaceflight for the United States Department of Defense (DoD) space science and technology community. STP is conducted by the Advanced Systems and Development Directorate, a directorate of the Space and Missile Systems Center of the United States Air Force.
Missions part of STP-27VPA:
- HALO-Net Free Flyer: is a 3U CubeSat with the main aim to test a retroreflectors array and to validate predicting models.
- Gunsmoke-J 4: is an experimental 3U CubeSat to test direct communications to Army combat operations.
- CNCE Blk.1 (1 and 3): are experimental CubeSats used to test advanced satellite-satellite communication.
Rocket 884: Progress (in Russian: "Прогресс") MS-17 is a Russian cargo vehicle which will resupply the International Space Station. This will be the 169th flight of a Progress.
Rocket 886: Yaogan-30 09 are a triplet of Chinese satellites of the Yaogan constellation. The purpose is not confirmed, although the news reports hint towards a SIGINT mission, especially to detect ships by their radio emissions. They are launched by triplet, in a similar way to the old American NOSS system, or to the Yaogan-31 constellation.
Rocket 887: GPS III (Global Positioning System) is the first evolution of the third generation of GPS satellites. The U.S. Air Force announced in May 2008 that a team led by Lockheed Martin had won the competition to build the next-generation Global Positioning System (Navstar) Space System program, known as GPS III.
Rocket 888: First Shenzhou flight since 2016. First crewed flight to the new Chinese modular space station.
Rocket 889: NROL-111 is a classified mission for the National Reconnoissance Office.
Rocket 890: Odyssey (TacRL-2) is a space domain awareness satellite that was procured under the Space Force's responsive launch program. The spacecraft was built in under a year and the launch provider was given three weeks of notice for the launch.
Rocket 891: 0.5 m resolution Earth observation satellite for Twenty First Century Aerospace Technology Company Ltd.
Rocket 892: SXM-8 is the ninth high-powered, digital, audio radio satellite built by Maxar (SSL) for SiriusXM. Built on Maxar’s 1300-class platform and designed to provide more than 15 years of service, SXM-8 is more than 8 meters tall and weighed nearly 7,000 kg at launch. SXM-8 has a large, mesh, unfurlable reflector almost 10 meters in diameter that allows SiriusXM programming to reach its radios, including those in moving vehicles.
Rocket 893: SpaceX CRS-22, also known as SpX-22, was a Commercial Resupply Service mission to the International Space Station. Dragon was docked to the station for 35 days before it successfully returned to Earth. 3,328kg of cargo were brought to the station, including the first of three pairs of iROSA solar arrays which will provide additional power to the station.
Rocket 894: Fengyun, abbreviated FY, are China's weather satellites. China has launched polar orbit and geosynchronous orbit meteorological satellites since 1988. The satellites in the FY-1 and FY-3 series are polar-orbiting sun-synchronous orbits. The satellites in the FY-2 and FY-4 series are in geosynchronous orbit.
Rocket 895: First cargo flight to the new Chinese space station.
Rocket 897: Final launch of the first shell of Starlink satellites.
Rocket 898: The flight incorporated all of the original test objectives from the previous test flight which was aborted early, including evaluating elements of the customer cabin, testing the live stream capability from the spaceship to the ground, and assessing the upgraded horizontal stabilizers and flight controls during the boost phase of the flight.
Rocket 900: The Space-Based Infrared System (SBIRS) is a consolidated system intended to meet the United States' infrared space surveillance needs through the first two to three decades of the 21st century. The SBIRS program is designed to provide key capabilities in the areas of missile warning, missile defense and battlespace characterization via satellites in geosynchronous earth orbit (GEO), sensors hosted on satellites in highly elliptical orbit (HEO), and ground-based data processing and control. SBIRS ground software integrates infrared sensor programs of the U.S. Air Force (USAF) with new IR sensors.
Rocket 901: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 902: 2nd stage Thrust Vector Control (TVC) system failed just after engine ignition due to engine igniter operations causing corruption of signals within the engine computer.
Rocket 903: First time a Falcon 9 booster flew for a 10th time, successfully completing the goal to fly a booster 10 times without significant refurbishment. Additionally, this is the fastest turnaround of droneship JRTI to date, at 10 days and 3 hours, beating its previous record by over 2 days.
Rocket 904: The purpose of the satellites is not confirmed, although the news reports hint towards a SIGINT mission, especially to detect ships by their radio emissions. They are also known as CX 5 by the manufacturer. They are launched by triplet, in a similar way to the old American NOSS system, or to the Yaogan-31 constellation.
Rocket 905: First successful landing of a Starship prototype. Although one of the 3 Raptor engines shut down early on ascent and was not able to relight, SN15 was still able to achieve a soft landing.
Rocket 906: SpaceX launched a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 907: Yaogan 34 is an optical remote sensing satellite, with a ground image resolution of a few meters, mainly used for land census, urban planning, land rights, road network design, crop yield estimation, and disaster prevention and mitigation. It was built by SAST.
Rocket 908: SpaceX will launch a batch of Starlink satellites for their high-speed low earth orbit internet constellation.
Rocket 909: First module of the new Chinese space station. Third Chinese space station, and the first modular space station to be launched this century.
Rocket 910: Flight VV-18. Return to flight for Vega after the VV17 failure.
Rocket 911: Qilu-1 is a synthetic aperture radar (SAR) remote sensing satellite and Qilu-4 is an optical remote sensing satellite, and both operate in the X-band for measurement and control data transmission.
Rocket 912: The KH-11 series, known as Kennen and Crystal, are American spy satellites utilizing electro-optical digital imaging for real-time observation, supplanting earlier film-return satellites. Manufactured by Lockheed, they likely incorporate a 2.4 m prime mirror, offering a theoretical 15 cm ground resolution. First launched by the American National Reconnaissance Office in December 1976, the KH-11 KENNEN was the inaugural American spy satellite to employ electro-optical digital imaging technology, enabling real-time optical observations.
Rocket 914: First SpaceX crewed mission to feature a flight-proven booster and the first SpaceX crewed mission to feature a flight-proven Dragon spacecraft. Crew Dragon Endeavour previously flew on the SpaceX Demo-2 mission.
Rocket 915: The NS-15 was an uncrewed test flight to verify that the launch vehicle and capsule are ready for crewed spaceflight. Before and after the launch, a crew boarded the spacecraft to simulate events that would occur during a real crewed flight.
